flowRoot.flowPara: The first step is to assemble and practice the use of your Foldscope. All the components and instructions are included and can be popped out of the cardboard net. Give yourselves some time to experiment with this before using our add-ons!

Follow our guide below to make simple PDMS silicon moulds from fragments of vinyl records & surplus electronics provided. The Foldscope is an elegant deceptively simple microscope, combining a ball lens like the first microscopes of Antonie van Leeuwenhoek with contemporary engineering practices and mass manufacturing. It's meant to help 'anyone' experience the microbiological world in a hands on way. You'll need to get quite intimate with your Foldscope equipment to get it to 'work' and be able to 'see' with it.

Make tiny environments with us & you get to intervene (for better or worse) in the microbiological world. Historian Ian Hacking thinks this is part of how we 'see' with microscopes and part of the everyday 'doing' of science.

Using everyday objects of our techno-scientific world, makes us think how much humans intervene in the world at all scales. What other objects in your worlds can you find that might make tiny spaces we can use? Go find some & take part in our research and tell us about it!

Labelled syringes filled with PDMS (A) & hardener (B). PDMS is a non-volatile silicon, safe to handle, but don't ingest it. We advise taking care to wash your hands thoroughly after use and store them in the plastic sleeves. Unmixed it can store for years so be careful not to cross contaminate. PDMS has amazing 'resolution', getting into the smallest nook & crannies of our worlds...
555 Timer chip. Common chip in maker projects and many electronic devices.
Micro-petri-dish with lid. Mix PDMS together and make impressions with chip surfaces. You could use anything you think might make tiny impressions in the surface of your PDMS mould.
* Look for the key features of the chip text so you know what to look for in the 'scope. They can be hard to find and less deep than our vinyl grooves.

* An open laptop screen with daylight helps illuminate while phone viewing. Move the phone and 'scope around to play with the light as it is refracted through the sample. Normally we only ever 'see' reflections of the surface of objects.
* Struggling with slabs? Try submerging the chip the other way up and keep checking the website for updates!

Vinyl fragment. Some of you may not remember, but at the dawn of pop culture and capitalism music was distributed widely on vinyl discs as micrometre scale grooves that could be amplified and played back for science & Little Richard

To use the glass slide you might need to insert it a few times as the card slots are very tight on first use. You can also make a minimal build of the Foldscope for phone viewing where you move the slide directly.

Prepare a paper slide following your foldscope instructions. We'll be using a live wet sample so we don't need to filter anything. Place a tiny drop of algal suspension on the slide/stickers then pick up the slab and lower it onto the sample. Use tissue to soak up excess sample & use the sticker cover slips included to 'seal' in the slab and liquid on the paper or glass slide

Use a sharp knife (not included) to cut a section out on the surface of the vinyl fragment. Use tweezers to lift this 'slab' of PDMS and carefully place just to the left of centre of your microscope slide 'groove' side down. As you lift it you'll see them shimmer in the light.
Cut around the chip and remove and it should pull a slab from the dish. Then cut around the chip surface & try to pull up a slab for your slide.
